d analysis of views and practices that shape cultural memory. Part one traces the historical and political relationship between Britain and Europe, whilst Part two is devoted to exemplary case studies of films as well as popular Eurosceptic and historical fiction. Part three engages with border mindedness and Britain’s island story. The book is addressed both to specialists in cultural studies, and a wider audience interested in Brexit.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBrexLit.  aBrexit.  aBritish exceptionalism.  aBritishness.  aCultural identity.  aCultural memory.  aEnglish literature.  aEnglishness.  aEuropean Union.  aEuroscepticism.  aIsland myth.1 aBischoff, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlagojevic, Blanka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeigel, Lara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabermann, Ina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHabermann, Ina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHerrschaft-Iden, Marlene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolland, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKüng, Melanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Alisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Connor, Siobhan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSanchez, M.G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchmitt-Kilb, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpiering, Menno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul